Sound Event Detection

Reynaldo Vazquez
June, 2019
GitHub Repo


This project builds an algorithm that automatically detects the occurrence of a sound event and its onset. An LSTM-based system that uses transformations of the mel spectrogram is able to achieve this with an event-based error rate of 0.06 and a F1-score of 0.97.

Motivation

Some sound events:

  • may signal the presence of an anomaly (i.e. machinery or vehicle malfunctions)
  • or alert about the existence of an emergency (i.e. gunshots, explosions, cries for help)
  • are rare
    • impractical to be continuously monitored by humans
    • sparsity of occurrences may cause lapses of attention (zoning out) in humans

Thus, monitoring for some sound events may be a good practice from a safety or security perspective, and automated monitoring may the be most efficient.

This project is inspired by Task 2: Detection of rare sound events of DCASE17 challenge. What differentiates this project from DCASE17's challenge is the introduction of confusing events in the audioset. In other words, this project builds a system that not only detects the occurrence of and event and its onset, but it discriminates between different types of events. The sound event to be detected is the occurrence of a glass break.

Data

Artificial sound mixes were created using background and event audio recordings from Tampere University's Detection and Classification of Acoustic Scenes and Events (DCASE) Community.

The created artificial audio dataset and meta data can be found here.

The source data can be found here.

Created artificial sound mixes are 10 seconds long and contain:

  • background audio from diverse scenes from start to end
  • some or none positive event (i.e. glass break sound)
  • some or none negative sounds (i.e. gunshot sound)

With this formula, two datasets were created separately: a training, and an evaluation dataset. These were created separately so that the backgrounds and event recordings used for the evaluation dataset were not used in any of the training audio mixes. Thus, keeping them unseen by the system during development. Meta-data was maintained documenting the source background, the overlaid source events, and the time onset and offset of each sound event or confusing sound.

Both datasets are almost perfectly balanced in terms of whether the event occurs in a track or not. However, since the main task of this study is to predict when, exactly in time, an event occurs, we should see the totals of each type of sound content in order to choose an appropriate performance metric. The following section does this.

To detect the onset of an event, the system will have to make predictions on segments of each audio track. The length of the segments chosen for the LSTM system is 47 milliseconds (i.e. 212 segments per track). With this in mind, and because the unbalanced nature of the dataset, event-based error rate, as defined in Mesaros and Heittola (2016) is used to evaluate the performance of the system. The formula to calculate it is:

where:

  • Insertions are events in the system output but not in ground truth

  • Deletions are events in ground truth but not in system output

As can be seen, with this metric true negative predictions have no use or meaning, i.e. the model is not 'rewarded' for correctly predicting the abscense of an event.

Model definition¶

LSTM-based model consists of 4 layers as follows

  • 1 temporal convolution (CONV1D) layer
  • 2 bidirectional-LSTM layers
  • 1 time distributed dense layer as output

with batch normalization and dropout with rate of 0.5 in all but the output layer.

In [27]:
drop_rate = 0.5
def model(input_shape):
    """
    Creates the model's graph in Keras.
    
    Argument:
    input_shape -- shape of the model's input data

    Returns:
    model -- Keras model instance
    """
    X_input = Input(shape = input_shape)
 
    X = Conv1D(128, kernel_size = 16, strides=4)(X_input)   
    X = BatchNormalization()(X)                             
    X = Activation('relu')(X)                               
    X = Dropout(drop_rate)(X)                               

    X = Bidirectional(LSTM(units = 64, return_sequences = True))(X) 
    X = Dropout(drop_rate)(X)
    X = BatchNormalization()(X)
    
    X = Bidirectional(LSTM(units = 64, return_sequences = True))(X) 
    X = Dropout(drop_rate)(X)
    X = BatchNormalization()(X)
    
    X = TimeDistributed(Dense(1, activation = "sigmoid"))(X)

    model = Model(inputs = X_input, outputs = X)
    return model

model = model(input_shape = (Tx, n_freq))
model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=["accuracy"])
model.summary()

Conclusion¶

This project built and tested a model for sound event detection. For this purpose, an artificial dataset with audio mixes was created using source recordings from Tampere's DCASE community. The dataset consists of audio clips that contain 0 to 4 mixed event occurrences.

The model presented is an LSTM-based deep learning implementation with one temporal convolution, two bidirectional-LSTM layers, and one time distributed dense layer as output. All but the output layers perform batch normalization for efficiency and dropout with rate of 0.5 to avoid overfitting.

The LSTM-based model is able to detect the occurrence of a sound event and its onset, while discriminating between different types of events achieving:

  • F1-score of 0.97
  • recall of 0.96
  • event-based error rate of 0.06.

More simply, it correctly detects 96 percent of event occurrences and their onset, missing 4 percent, and falsely detecting an event at a 2 percent rate.

Reference:¶

Annamaria Mesaros, Toni Heittola, and Tuomas Virtanen, Metrics for polyphonic sound event detection, Applied Sciences, 6(6):162, 2016
